fields.title: The Complete Microsoft Planner Tutorial for Beginners
fields.body:
What is Microsoft Planner

Microsoft planner is an app of Microsoft that helps you organize and efficiently keep your work. You can create tasks and to-do lists and organize everything in a structured way for your team or company to view. It is almost like Trello if you have used it. In this Microsoft planner tutorial, we will see the different benefits and usage of the Microsoft Planner.

The main use of the Microsoft planner is that you get a clear idea of what you are working on as well as your team and make updates to the work. It helps the team to have a smooth workflow and know the status of the tasks. In short, it is a visual and simple way to organize teamwork. You need an Office 365 subscription to use the Planner whether that be personal or enterprise.

Microsoft Planner Review

Let’s see some of the features of the Microsoft Planner. This Microsoft Planner tutorial will help you to get a clear understanding of the various concepts.

Assigning Tasks

Within the Microsoft Planner, you can assign a particular task to a specific team member. You can write the title of the tasks, fill in all the details and then assign a team member to do it with a specified date. You can even assign a particular task to any number of team members.

Share Files

You can share files with your team members inside the Planner. Once you assign a task to a specific team member there is an option to attach a file. This makes it easy for you to have some extra details for your tasks.

Collaboration Through Chat

You can also communicate with your team members through the chat facility in the Planner. This feature helps in easy communication and real-time updates.

Easy Navigation

The Planner allows you to create buckets. Under each bucket, one can add multiple tasks. For example, there can be ongoing, not started, completed buckets for a plan. You can add multiple tasks under each bucket. So probably there will be different buckets and you can easily navigate through them through the filter option available in Planner. You can filter by the assigned person, the due date, categories, and more.

Easy Integration

Within the Planner, you can integrate it with the Microsoft apps like Excel, SharePoint, Outlook, Microsoft Teams, etc. This is a very powerful feature as it makes the Planner more productive.

Building a Plan in the Microsoft Planner

Now in this Microsoft Planner Tutorial, let us see how we can create a plan inside the Planner. A plan is the first thing you need to create inside the Planner to get started. Inside each plan, you will create tasks and all the organizing. A plan is the main project. You can create multiple plans for each of the projects.

  1. Once inside the Planner, on the left-hand side click on the new plan.
  2. Then give the plan a name.
  3. Now you can invite an existing Microsoft group to your plan. This is optional.
  4. Next, decide whether you want the plan to be public or private. In public, your plan can be seen by the whole organization. In private, the plan can be seen only by the members you add to your plan.
  5. Write a group description. Again, this is optional.
  6. Click Create a plan.

Adding Other Members to Your Plan

The next thing you are going t learn in this Microsoft Planner Tutorial is adding members to the plan. You can add as many members as you want to your plan. All the members you add to the plan will be able to see and edit inside the Plan. For this click on the members tab on the top right-hand side of the Planner. Then enter the name of the member and click enter. For each plan, you can add different members based on the project you are working on.

A member in one plan will not be able o see other plan members and the tasks. In short, you can manage multiple plans inside a planner with multiple team members. You can also delete team members as you wish. Assigning a task to team members is another thing you can do inside each plan.

Adding Tasks and Assigning Them

By default, when you create a plan, you will see a to-do bucket in the planner. You can add tasks under this bucket or can create new ones. It depends upon the task you need to add and assign. Now let’s see how we can add and assign a task in this Microsoft Planner Tutorial.

  1. Under the bucket, you want to add the task, click add task.
  2. Then enter a name for your task.
  3. Click on the set the due date button. You will see an option to set the due date. Set the due date for the task.
  4. Now choose the member to whom you want to assign the task. For this click on the assign button. Until you assign the task, it will show unassigned.
  5. Lastly, click on the add task button for your task to appear as a card, under the bucket.

(You can also add extra details for your task by clicking on the card. A new window will open and you can enter the details there).

Staying On Track

Now in this Microsoft Planner Tutorial, let’s plan how we can get a detailed and clear overview of the plan.

Charts

The chart shows the complete status of the plan like how many tasks are under a bucket, a chart depicting how many tasks come under each priority level (urgent, important, medium, and low), a list of the members of the plan, and the number of tasks each person has been assigned with. Charts help to get a detailed and clear overview of the complete plan with its various features.

Schedule

The schedule gives a calendar view of all the tasks in a plan. This is easy for you to understand which task is approaching and which ones need more care, etc. You will get the complete dates in the plan with the calendar tab.

Other Options

To the right side of the schedule tab, you will see three dots. If you click on them, you will see a list of items namely, conversation, members, files, notebook, and sites.

Conversation – Clicking on a conversation will take you directly to outlook so that you can email team members from there.

Members – Clicking on members will get you to the group membership page where you will be able to add and delete members.

Files – Clicking on files will take you to the group's SharePoint library, where you can edit, add, delete the files related to the plan.

Notebook – Selecting Notebook will take you to the OneNote Notebook that is dedicated to your plan.

Sites – Sies will take you to SharePoint where you can create and edit a new site.

You are also able to make a copy of your plan or add the plan to your favorites. Once you add the plan to the favorites, it appears on the top of the planner and you can easily select it for future actions. You are also able to export your plan to excel and copy its link so you can share it with anyone you want. Once a task is completed on the plan, the assigned person can mark it as complete and the task will be hidden. If needed you can expand the task.

Getting Updates on the Plan

The members of a plan can enable notifications for all the tasks assigned to them and for tasks that are due shortly. This is very helpful as the members can be notified whenever a task becomes active or important. The team member to whom the task is assigned will get an email notifying that the task has been assigned. This is an easy way to get the team members to know the progress and the status of the tasks. It is always nice to turn this setting on as it will help the team in better collaboration.

Wrapping Up

Microsoft Planner is an app that helps organizations and teams to get organized and create plans to work on projects. The app helps to work as a team and assign tasks to members. The app is used by many organizations across the globe to make their work more meaningful and impactful. Integration with the Office 365 apps makes the Planner more efficient and convenient to use. Everything is easy and readily available within the planner to access.

You need a subscription to use the planner and it is worth it if you are an organization or someone who leads a team. Microsoft is continuously updating the features in the software and we will see more interesting and useful updates in the future. This Microsoft Planner Tutorial has covered everything you need to know about Planner and the ways it can be used. Hope you enjoyed the tutorial and wish you all the best in using Microsoft Planner.

fields.intro: Microsoft Forms is an application developed by Microsoft for the users to create quizzes, surveys, questionnaires, etc.
fields.title: Microsoft Forms Tutorial: The Complete Guide
fields.body:
What is Microsoft Forms

Microsoft Forms is an application developed by Microsoft for the users to create quizzes, surveys, questionnaires, etc. The user can create forms according to his choice and subject matter. These forms once created can be shared with people to collect responses. Microsoft forms also show the responses users have given to the form with all the detailed analysis. Creating a form is simple and anyone with basic computer knowledge can do it. Anyway, there are some things you need to know to work on the forms and in this Microsoft Forms Tutorial, we will let you know all those.

How To Access Forms

To access Microsoft forms all, you need to do is to go to office.com and select forms from the list. Then you will be inside the form creation tool. From here you can start creating awesome looing forms that serve your purpose.

How to Create a Form

Let us see how to create a form in this Microsoft Forms Tutorial.

  1. Sign in to your Microsoft account in Office.com and on the dashboard, click on Forms.
  2. Select New Form.
  3. Enter the title and description for your form.
  4. Add the questions. You will see an add a question option. Click on it.
  5. There are different types of questions you can add to the form like text, choice, rating, and date. You can also select more question types for Likert, ranking, net promoter score, or file upload. To create a new section, click on the section.

Previewing the Form

You can always preview your form anytime you need. The preview button is available on the right-hand corner of the screen. Once you click it you can have both desktop and mobile previews. Previewing the form is helpful as it enables you to have a look at your form as and when you finish doing something new.

Adding Themes in the Microsoft Forms

Now, in this Microsoft Forms Tutorial, let us see how we can add themes. There are different themes in the Microsoft forms and you can select a theme that is suitable for your form. This option is available in the themes button on the right-hand side of the screen. Once you click the themes button you will see different themes available. You can upload the one that best fits you. You can also make a custom theme of your choice if you need to. Also, you can upload themes from your computer. Themes make your forms attractive and user-friendly. You can also change the background of the forms as needed. If you have an eye for creativity, then you can play around and see what best fits you.

Sharing the Form and Collecting Responses

Once you have created the form you are ready to share it with others and collect responses. You can also share the form with your team members for collaboration.

  1. Click on the Share button in the right-hand corner.
  2. A box will appear with a drop-down list. You will see the options such as ‘Anyone can respond’ ‘Only people in my organization can respond’ ‘Particular people in my organization can respond’.
    Anyone can respond – This option makes anyone you send the form to or come in contact with it can respond. These are usually used for getting responses for surveys and questionnaires
    Only people in my organization can respond – This option makes it possible for members within your organization, you have signed with a work or school account can respond.
    Particular people in my organization can respond – This option makes it possible for specific people or groups whom the author mentions inside the organization to respond to the firm.
  3. Select the copy link button to copy the link for the form. Alternatively, you can access the link to the form in case you need to collaborate with people.
  4. There are options such as QR code, embedded URL, and an option to send the form via email also. You can make use of these according to your convenience.

Export the Form Responses as an Excel File

Exporting the form to an Excel file is easy and we will see how it is done in this Microsoft Forms Tutorial. Once you start getting responses for your form, you can see all your responses in the responses tab. You will see an option to export your form responses via excel. By clicking on it you can download the responses as an MS Excel file. This will give you an easy and clear picture of the responses got with all the details. You can store this on your personal computer and access it whenever you need it. You can also make modifications to this data at your convenience.

Accessibility of Microsoft Forms

  • Microsoft Forms is a worldwide application and is available in 60 languages.
  • Microsoft forms feature screen reader accessibility. This means that people with vision impairments can use it. An immersive reader facility is also available so that the form is ready to read aloud.
  • Microsoft forms allow easy navigation through the keyboard so that anyone can use it with all the facilities.

Using Forms Inside Microsoft Teams

If you are using Microsoft Teams you can easily integrate the forms inside it. This will help you to make your work and collaboration more interesting and meaningful. You can ask the team members to share their opinion and make them see the results of the responses in the form. This means that whenever someone gives a response to the form, your team members will be able to see it inside Microsoft teams.You can also create a form to collect responses from your team members inside Microsoft Teams. The whole process is super easy and you can use everything in one place. This helps you to organize activities and effectively manage tasks.

Benefits of Microsoft Forms

Now in this Microsoft forms tutorial, we will discuss some of the benefits of Microsoft Forms. Microsoft forms have a wide range of benefits and it is useful in any industry. The forms are very helpful in education where students and universities can make forms and use them for academic purposes.

  • Collect Great Data and Make Better Decisions – With Microsoft forms, you can make better decisions. You can collect any number of data and make decisions with them. Forms are great for data collection. It is easy for you to analyze the data with the responses received. There is a separate tab in forms, where you can see all the responses and make informative decisions. You can even export the data received to MS Excel to get a precise and better understanding of things.
  • Easily Get the Information you Need – With Microsoft forms you can easily get the information you need. Whatever be your information need, you can get it through Microsoft forms. All you need to do is to create a form and then share it with the people you want the responses from.
  • Grow your Business – Businesses need to collect data. This can be from customers, suppliers, or any other stakeholders. You can collect precious data and then use that data to make meaningful business decisions. This will eventually result in better productivity and results for the business.
  • Increase your Reach – The best way to increase your reach is to get your form in front of as many people as possible. This can be done by integrating Microsoft forms with many applications online. This in turn will increase your reach and get more leads.
  • Stay Connected on the Go – It doesn’t matter where you are in the world, whether you are traveling or in a meeting. Microsoft Forms is accessible through any web browser and there is a mobile app for the same. This will help you to use the forms wherever you are and from whichever device you are using, a desktop or a smartphone. These are some of the benefits of Microsoft Forms. The benefits are not limited to these and you can use forms in any aspect of your life. The uses are endless and you can always get connected with it.

Conclusion

We have learned a lot about Microsoft Forms in this Microsoft Forms Tutorial. Microsoft Forms are a great application developed by Microsoft to create and share forms. One can create any kind of form for any purpose. It is easy to create forms with Microsoft Forms and the interface is friendly and easy to navigate. You can also integrate forms to different applications and also to Microsoft Teams. In the ever-evolving world of online education and other sectors, Microsoft Forms are really helpful.

Whether you are running a business or is a team leader, then Microsoft forms are really handy for you. It will make your work easier and help you sort out things quickly. Sometimes you may need to have a quick form ready to fill out customer data or to send to your supplier. Microsoft forms will help you in all these situations with no trouble. Try to use Microsoft Forms and get the most out of it and enjoy the experience. Hope you enjoyed this Microsoft Forms Tutorial. We wish you a fruitful and successful Microsoft Forms use.

fields.intro: One of the signature features of the balanced scorecard is that it looks at organizational performance from various
fields.title: The 8 Perspectives Of A Balanced Scorecard: How To Use Them To Improve Performance
fields.body:
One of the signature features of the balanced scorecard is that it looks at organizational performance from various.

Introduction

As the name implies, there are four perspectives on a balanced scorecard. There are three strategic perspectives that are used to guide and analyze the various strategic aspects of the organization.

  • The first perspective is organizational governance, which looks at governance processes.
  • The second perspective is on knowledge, which focuses on the accumulation of knowledge.
  • The third perspective is about organizational culture, which helps in understanding how the organization looks at the customers, community, environment, etc.
  • The fourth and final perspective is on people and their performance. This perspective examines the overall people's effectiveness, as well as individual performance.

Why the Balanced Scorecard?

  1. The Balanced Scorecard highlights data from two major parts: the organizational and customer. They need to be linked to each other for overall, organizational, and customer success. Organizations (employees, product/service owners, management, etc.) all need to work together to drive this process.
  2. The three-tier approach of the three different perspectives gives the organization a roadmap to achieve sustained top performance.
  3. The Balanced Scorecard helps to ensure stakeholder buy-in. The stakeholders are not seen as one “silo” rather, they are viewed as playing a role in achieving the customer goals. By establishing a framework to maximize shared goals, they will become stakeholders in the success of the organization.

Below are the four perspectives:

1. Customers

These fall under broad categories such as Sales, Service, and Customer Service. The long-term impact of these on a company is their very nature – those are persistent, can't be altered (or if they can, can be altered very gradually), and play a large part in getting a business to succeed and stay afloat. Leads Not used to high-profile relevance and therefore getting lesser-valued. Taken into the light when an online marketing campaign or email marketing service releases an email campaign, leads are the bread-and-butter of those services. For example, going on an online marketing campaign could lead to an increase in the number of leads generated from the targeted campaign.

Managers select the consumer and stakeholder categories in which the product line will contend, as well as the measurements of the business unit's success in these product lines, under the customer viewpoint of the Balanced Scorecard. Several fundamental or general metrics of positive results from a well-formulated and executed plan are often included in this approach.

Customer satisfaction, employee satisfaction, retaining existing customers, customer profitability, and profitability in selected categories are among the key assessment tools. However, precise indicators of the pricing strategies that the firm will offer to clients in specified business sectors should be included in the customer viewpoint.

2. Learning and Growth

The learning and growth viewpoint focuses on people's skills for reward reasons. Managers would be in charge of enhancing employee talents.

Staff happiness, employee retention, and employee productivity are all important factors to consider when evaluating a manager's success.

Staff Satisfaction:

Staff satisfaction recognizes the significance of staff motivation in increasing efficiency, performance, service quality, and contextual reaction. Employee satisfaction may be assessed by distributing questionnaires, interviewing workers, or monitoring them at work.

Maintenance of Employees:

Employees generate organization-specific intellectual capital and provide a valuable non-financial asset to firms that are dedicated to maintaining them. Firms also suffer expenditures when they need to identify and recruit strong expertise to replace departing employees. Employee retention is calculated as the inverse of staff turnover, or the percentage of employees that depart each year.

The efficiency of Employees:

The significance of output per worker is acknowledged by worker productivity. Employees produce either financial or physical yield. A basic metric of productivity for loan officers in a financial institution would also be the number of loans handled per loan officer each month.

3. Economic

Some are numbers. In this instance, the balance sheet reflects the profitability and capital strength of the organization. Some are events. Perhaps the opening of a new facility, a major program launch, or a major acquisition. The scorecard reports that as an event. Some are process management. At the corporate level, we might consider organizational performance as a result of process management. For a unit of the organization, we might examine process management for the achievement of unit goals. The aggregate result is the accomplishment of corporate and unit goals. There is also quality. While it is important to look at the overall quality of the company as a whole, we may also look at the different outcomes within a particular segment of the business.

Financial performance metrics, such as net income and return on investment, are used in the balanced scorecard since they are used among profit-making firms. Financial results indicators serve as a standard language for evaluating businesses. Financial institutions and stockholders, for example, rely significantly on financial performance metrics when determining whether to loan or make investments to firms. Financial measurements that are well-designed can offer an overall picture of an organization's success. Financial incentives aren't enough to motivate people to succeed. Financial indicators provide background information, but not about the long term.

4. Internal Systems

Internal systems involve your departments and functions and even the people who are working in the organization. Such internal systems work according to their own rules, while other ones are governed by external rules. One example of external rules is the rules of the government. The rules of the various regulatory agencies regulate how an organization must conduct itself. For example, government regulations regulate whether a company may acquire another company or how many shares may be owned, and what percentage each shareholder can own. Internal rules are associated with different departments and functions within an organization and are largely self-regulated.

Controlling processes to generate dependable and reliable items/products is the key to greatness in every business. Constant rates of quality of products and services are achieved by following the correct procedures in the proper order. Finding the correct operating conditions to evaluate and defining criteria suited to the levels of performance from each of the measurement methods is the tough part. Technical and operational measures are cutting-edge, brief initiatives.

These are all the metrics that are generally tracked on a routine basis. Some control parameters also are regularly reviewed to guarantee that greater services and products are produced and delivered. Good process or operational performance contributes to increased services and products, which contributes to delighted or ecstatic clients, which results in repeat business and boosts an organization's future performance and growth. An organization's inputs must be controlled in order to attain consistent excellent productivity. Understanding client requirements and high-quality products and services are the two most essential elements to great results.

Balancing Perspectives

Each page of the scorecard layout represents a different viewpoint. For example, our projects page highlights projects that go through regular reviews or management reviews as well as project teams who meet regularly. Several things are different on our finance page, including a reference to the value of our company's assets, how much we pay our employees in cash, and the debt status of our company. We also highlight our investment activities in terms of risk and return in both absolute and relative terms. These perspectives add value by highlighting positive and negative aspects of our performance as well as the respective paths we can take to improve.

Pros of a Scorecard-Specific Application:

  • It is usually extremely good at maintaining the Balanced Scorecard and can do so right away.
  • It can accommodate a large number of users.
  • It has the ability to generate the reports you require.

Cons:

  • It's possible that you'll have difficulties connecting to other programs at times.
  • It has a steep learning curve.
  • It may be rather costly.
  • Some people are not adaptable.

Business Processes

The "work in progress" is the work that you've done, but the challenge is turning it into something that people can take advantage of in their everyday activities.

Inventory: All of the inventory in your organization is something you've gotten, but the challenge is knowing what you have, how you're using it, and whether you should be getting more of it or some other item instead.

Counting: The way you count things is just as important as how you count them. It's critical to know if you have your numbers right.

The Daily Barometer: If you've ever done a quick organizational or planning exercise in the morning, you understand the need to get a barometer on how things are going.

Conclusion

Over the past decade, organizations have widely adopted a new development framework and measurement practice called the balanced scorecard. There is a growing evidence base showing that balanced scorecards have benefits for organizations and their customers. Balanced scorecards are a very powerful development framework and are likely to be used in more companies in the coming years. However, like all frameworks, we should learn from the errors that exist with the implementation of the balanced scorecard. The time has come for chief executives to publicly admit that strategic planning and measurement have broken down. In many ways, they have.

Whilst the balanced scorecard is a proven and true approach with several potential benefits, it's vital to examine your company's performance and whether or not a balanced scorecard sysstem is worth the cost.

fields.intro: Business intelligence and analytics are data management solutions implemented in companies and enterprises to collect
fields.title: The Complete Guide to Business Intelligence and Analytics: For Beginners and Experts
fields.body:
Business intelligence and analytics are data management solutions implemented in companies and enterprises to collect historical and present data, while using statistics and software to analyze raw information, and deliver insights for making better future decisions.

What are BI and Analytics?

Business intelligence and analytics involve collecting, analyzing, and presenting structured and unstructured data to give better insights to the employees. Data, in this case, includes customer data, user information, and product/service/supply chain data. BI solutions and analytics tools focus on analyzing data and predicting future events. Instead of analyzing historical data, these solutions can analyze and predict future events. This allows companies to prepare and present to employees, products, and business partners about upcoming events and trends.

Business intelligence (BI)

Business intelligence (BI) is the process of observing, gathering, and analyzing data to make informed business choices. Because there is so much data out there, BI assists businesses in filtering through existing relevant data to interpret historical and present trends and patterns to make better decisions for current operations. In many businesses, business intelligence analysts collaborate alongside data scientists to evaluate the collected data, understand data trends, and then successfully explain to their employers how to best apply these results.

Financial analysts, academic researchers, and data systems analysts may use business intelligence, depending on the business and sector within a company. Organizations can gather and understand raw data, make educated and rapid choices in the present, and analyze data in real-time thanks to business intelligence and the analysts who guide the field.

Business analytics (BA)

Business analytics (BA) is critical to maximizing the value of business intelligence by interpreting data and predicting future patterns based on existing data. Businesses that want to enhance or alter their present operations and make better judgments in the future can benefit from business analytics. Based on an examination of why things happened in the past and if something will happen again, it may be used to strategy, discover sales and market possibilities, enhance customer relationships, better indicate potential hazards, and reduce dangers.

What is Data Management?

For an entire discussion on data management, let’s understand what it is. According to Wikipedia, “data management is the overarching discipline of controlling, managing, and manipulating digital information.” To be able to efficiently use data, people need to have an understanding of the various models of data management including data architecture, data lineage, data collection techniques, data movement, data classification, data comparison, data deletion, data discovery, data sharing, data stewardship, data classification, data maintenance, and data compliance. All of this is in a continuous cycle and further addressed in the data science roles. In the early days of computing, data was stored in the primary storage device and had limited availability.

The data management process involves several tasks that work together to ensure that data in business systems is correct, accessible, and available. The majority of the work is done by IT and data management teams, although business users are usually involved in various portions of the process to ensure that the data fit their needs and to get their support.

The Importance of Data Management

But the problem is, we often hear about collecting this and analyzing it, but we rarely hear about data cleanliness and monitoring the data. Now, the biggest concern here is that the organization is not using the right technology to keep the data from going stale, safe, and compliant. There is a different kind of devices used for business intelligence and analytics which require an amount of storage and processing power which is not available in most of the countries. So, the main issue with this is the manual process. The process can’t be automated so easily and is expensive and burdensome. The total amount of data in this space is just not acceptable. It has doubled in the last five years.

  • Duplicate files are frequently produced while processing data in file-based data management systems. Many copies of the same file may be kept at various locations inside a server or even across various systems. Data redundancy arises as a result of this. However, extra labor and space are required to resolve or decrease these files.
  • DMS allows you to exchange data among the database's authorized users. Complete access to a database belongs to the management, and only the authorized person, after confirming all protocols, may give the level of access to other users.
  • Your data's integrity and security are ensured by DMS. Data integrity relates to data reliability and uniformity while dealing with huge amounts of data spread across several databases. A variety of individuals can access these databases, and the information can subsequently be used to make business choices. As an outcome, it's critical to provide only reliable and timely data to all customers.
  • One of the most serious problems that businesses confront is data loss. In a conventional file processing system, you must backup the database regularly, which wastes a lot of time and resources. Furthermore, the procedure will take a long time if you have a significant volume of data.

Types of Business Intelligence

On one end of the spectrum, various types of business intelligence analyze financial data like growth, revenues, spending, loss, profitability, and others. Another type of business intelligence analyzes sales performance. A third type is based on geographic data and analyzes the potential growth of a company’s business in different regions. The fourth category of business intelligence is that it collects natural data like social media and web information. Types of Business Analytics A classification of business intelligence is based on the sort of data that is captured.

Types of Analytics

Data analytics encompasses a wide range of models. The simplest forms of data analytics are in-depth analysis of a single data set. This type of analysis is used to estimate the likelihood of something happening. Some examples of this type of analytics are forecasting, anomaly detection, and trend identification. While this type of analytics is straightforward, many types of data analytics add richness to the analysis. For instance, the exploratory analysis will determine what specific data is being analyzed. This type of analysis is used to understand the properties of an analytic problem, without being limited to any particular data set. The possibilities are endless, and there are numerous ways to incorporate this type of analytics into a company.

The capacity to mine data, statistically evaluate events and why they occurred, test prior choices, and undertake predictive forecasts are all advantages of business analytics. Organizations may prepare without having to respond to market shifts thanks to the predictive models given by business analytics. Instead, they can work proactively based on aggregate data that predicts future results.

Because business intelligence focuses on current conditions and business analytics determines future scenarios, integrating the two might help a company better attain present and future business solutions.

Business intelligence vs Business analytics

  • Business Analytics employs prior data to extract information and manage business operations that drive consumer requirements and enhance productivity, whereas Business Intelligence incorporates both past and present data.
  • Business Intelligence is primarily concerned with reporting the studied data, whereas Business Analytics is concerned with a variety of tools that conduct various operational applications with various instruments.
  • Business Intelligence is virtually synonymous with Business Analytics, which encompasses BI, data warehousing, information management, enterprise applications, governance, risk, and security compliances.
  • Business Analytics will use Business Intelligence reports as inputs to process the extracted information in a more complex way to visualize the studied data, whereas Business Intelligence is a method of evaluating existing data.
  • Business Intelligence employs data study, predictive modeling, and predictive modeling to establish current patterns and determine the causes of current events or results, but Business Analytics cannot retrieve, analyze, report, and publish large volumes of data.
  • Business Intelligence refers to the content of the data you have on hand, whereas Business Analytics refers to how you use or operate on that data to get insights from it.
  • Business intelligence is mostly about gaining access to large amounts of data. Business analytics is the application of several cutting-edge technical techniques to deal with large amounts of data.
  • Business Intelligence is used to successfully manage firms, whereas Business Analytics is a method of altering a business to make it more efficient and effective in its operations.

The Importance of Data Quality

Data quality is key to business intelligence and analytics, as the results produced by analytics tools can only be trusted if the data is properly categorized and its quality is high.

It might be difficult to collect high-quality data. When a firm tries to combine multiple systems across different departments or services, install new software, or manually enter data, data quality issues might arise. They may also emerge as a result of a company's lack of appropriate tools or processes. However, there are things that businesses can do to assist enhance data quality. The steps below can assist in the collecting of high-quality data.

  1. Develop a data collection method: You'll need a data collection plan in place to guarantee that the data you're gathering is of good quality. Determine the kind of data you'll need to achieve your objectives, as well as the techniques you'll employ to gather and manage it. You should also specify the responsibilities of all people involved in data collection and develop protocols for how you'll communicate data-related issues amongst departments in your plan. To minimize misunderstanding and to guarantee that you can track your success, be explicit in your strategy.
  2. Establish data quality requirements: Establish data quality requirements to help you decide which data to preserve, which to discard, and which to repair. These criteria should be agreed upon and understood by everyone involved in data management. This provides uniformity throughout your company.
  3. Make a data-correction strategy: You'll need to establish data-correction guidelines. These guidelines should specify who is accountable for data correction and what techniques should be used to do so. This is also crucial for maintaining data consistency.

Conclusion

To grow the business as a professional in analytics, you should select a data management software and one that you can become familiar with. Then you will need to engage and work with people within your organization to collect data. Following the explanation above, you will be able to deploy analytics in your work.

fields.intro: The technique of using a BI tool to gather and evaluate information and identify and convey profound influences is referred
fields.title: The Complete Guide to Business Intelligence Reporting
fields.body:
The technique of using a BI tool to gather and evaluate information and identify and convey profound influences is referred to as business intelligence reporting.BI reporting aids people in making smart decisions and increasing operational efficiency in this way.

What is Business Intelligence Reporting?

Business Intelligence Reporting is the application of analytic software to gather information from disparate sources and evaluate the data to create in a report a fuller picture of the company. BI reporting offers a variety of features that make it suitable for use in various business areas. BI reporting can be broadly divided into two main categories:

Analysis reporting is the recording of empirical data, the modification of it, and the expression of it into simple reports that are delivered to others.

Reproduction reporting is the management of data to provide the same outputs to the same agents at a later stage. This helps the employee in determining where the error occurred and how to solve it.

Why use Business Intelligence Reporting?

Fifty years ago, communication was delivered by mail or telegram. Even if the recipient was available, it was very difficult for them to understand what was being communicated. Now, many business reporters no longer have to communicate in person or over the phone. Business reporters can simply send information via e-mail, send a notification to a secure group, or even speak directly with one of the newsroom teams. This allows the news organizations to quickly and efficiently pass on important information regarding business outcomes and operations. As a result, business reporters can get information from the right person and create deeper insights about the organization. They can do this by leveraging advanced and flexible BI tools.

The Process of Business Intelligence Reporting

If you want to get a true understanding of what business intelligence reporting is about, then let’s get started. Before we start, let us go over a few topics about BI reporting. Why you need BI Reporting? Knowing what you need is a critical first step before you start the process of business intelligence reporting. This article can help you focus in the right direction. Once you’ve understood the potential of business intelligence reporting, then let’s get down to business. To summarize, here is a brief list of what you need to do in the process of business intelligence reporting:

The Tools of BI Reporting

The list of the appropriate business intelligence tools to analyze data is very large, and one needs to select the best one with the assistance of appropriate reading, training, experience, and study. As far as data analysis software is concerned, BI tools can be divided into two main groups: relational and non-relational. The latter include the BI tools of non-relational technology, with the main purpose being to cut across data sources, systems, and applications. The most popular relational tools are R, Python, Excel, Java, Ruby on Rails, and PHP. Additionally, enterprise data mining and statistics software, such as SAS and SPSS, are also relational tools, providing the user the flexibility to analyze data in the relational form and also to query multiple tables.

Tools for BI Reporting

Business intelligence reporting can be accomplished using three different tools.

Analog Dashboards:

Analog dashboard is just a visual representation of a digital dashboard. It is often used to view data in tables and graphs to identify commonalities or patterns that may influence business operations.

A Day by Day/ Week by Week/ Month by Month Progress Report

This reporting format documents business process tasks in an actual chronological sequence. It does not include any data, but it shows every task carried out and its result.

A Lookback Report

This report does not have any details of input of the task but uses metrics to show the progress over time. It is useful to understand the daily progress and break down work done per day and per week in the past.

Managing Information

The method of analyzing and reporting data is an important part of a large company's work culture. BI tools enable an individual or organization to identify relevant information from an appropriate repository and then to understand it and evaluate its relevance.

Analyzing and Reporting Results

When attempting to report and present information, BI professionals have to be careful with their choice of words to convey relevant data understandably. Using the right vocabulary helps the users deliver more accurate and credible results.

Discussing BI Skills

BI professionals have specific, logical skills needed to create, share, integrate and interpret data. These skills can range from data visualization, information technology, data engineering, and theory to statistics and keywords.

The Future of Business Intelligence Reporting

BI and reporting seem to be very similar techniques and the merging of the two has become a trend in many organizations. Though much thought has been put into the actual process of data presentation, the outcome is still the same. Now a couple of years down the road, all that's going to change. In this digital age where data and analytics are far more important than ever, BI tools have taken over, and they are becoming the most sought-after part of any report.

Business Intelligence And Reporting's Advantages

If a corporation approaches reporting appropriately and strategically, it can earn a lot of benefits. The basic purpose of business intelligence reports is to give complete data that can be quickly accessed, comprehended, and used to make decisions.

Increasing the efficiency of the workflow

Managers, staff, and key stakeholders are frequently stranded while expecting a full BI report from IT or SQL developers. Especially if a business connects data from many sources. The procedure can take many days, slowing down the workflow. Actions can't be made, analyses can't be completed, and the entire firm suffers as a result.

Any business or division can use it.

For any department, staff, or manager, building an effective BI report might be a demanding endeavor. Cost savings and increased efficiency are two goals of generating successful, informative reports. One business report illustration might be about finance, while another would be about sales, and yet another might be about marketing. It is dependent on a company's or department's specific requirements. With its multiple capabilities, financial analytics can be maintained under control, removing complications and establishing clean and different opportunities for all the financial data a company maintains.

Real-time and historical data are also used.

The large volume of obtained data is difficult to use and grasp using typical reporting methods. Even the most seasoned executives may find it difficult to create a straightforward presentation from a large amount of data. Because historical data is also offered in an online reporting platform that can analyze and produce all the business data required, reports in business intelligence are a valuable reference. Another important consideration is the ability to use real-time data. The level of intricacy that may be achieved in BI projects cannot be matched to traditional reporting.

Forecasting and operational optimization

To monitor and analyze progress, every significant firm employs key performance indicators. There are a plethora of KPI examples to choose from and incorporate into a strategy, but only proper tracking and evaluation will yield beneficial results. Business intelligence and reporting aren't only about tracking data; they also include forecasting based on descriptive analytics and artificial intelligence, which could save time and money by preventing costly and time-consuming investment choices. As a result, reporting in business intelligence is showcased from a variety of perspectives that can reveal insights that would otherwise go unnoticed.

Strategic decision-making that is well-informed

It's critical to leverage digital data to streamline the business when it comes to an ultimate decision or strategy formulation. BI reporting platforms are simple to use, visually appealing, and provide a lot of important information, allowing you to quickly discover patterns, identify possible weaknesses and strengths, and unearth groundbreaking discoveries.BI will enable you to make quick, educated plans and determine actionable milestones or benchmarks based on solid data, whether you'd like to simplify your budget, create a tailored advertising campaign, enhance an internal procedure, or anything else you can think of.

More efficient procurement procedures

Among the most important advantages of BI-based reporting would be that, when presented understandably, they provide access to logical structures and discoveries that can help you improve the efficiency of critical areas of your organization. This is especially true if your business involves a big volume of items and/or services. But if that's the situation, you almost certainly must have had some sort of procurement department. Your procurement procedures are critical to your company's overall performance and long-term viability since its functioning will pervade all aspects of the firm.

Data quality has improved

Among the most obvious and strong advantages of advanced analytics for business is that it allows users to extract every last ounce of potential from their resources. Identifying which findings and indicators have actual value in a digital company world where fresh data is generated at a fast pace is a minefield. Intelligent data analytics might seem hard to achieve with so much data and so little time.

Management of human resources and performance evaluations

Last but not least, in our comprehensive examination of BI advantages, we'll look at how BI-centric reports may help with performance evaluation. It's simple to spot productivity patterns, compare important indicators, and focus on the individual performance when you have streamlined exposure to performance-based KPIs. You may accelerate your company's success in a major manner by doing so. By having access to dynamic visual information based on the individual and collective performance of employees, you can provide training and assistance to your employees as needed, while establishing leader boards to motivate everyone to strive toward a common goal.

Conclusion

Business intelligence software is in great demand today because it is great to use. It is easy to use and proficient as it is rather flexible. This trend is best witnessed in different verticals, including government, retail, and other areas where large quantities of data are involved.

fields.intro: Data mining is a task to extract meaningful information from a large amount of available data
fields.title: Data Mining Concepts and Techniques: A Beginner's Guide
fields.body:
Here are some of the concepts and techniques in processing gathered data or information, which will be used in various applications. Specifically, it explains data mining and the tools used in discovering knowledge from the collected data.

What is Data Mining?

Data mining is a task to extract meaningful information from a large amount of available data. When data is fed into a process, it would look for patterns. However, when enough data is fed, patterns will be found in the information. The information that is usually retrieved through data mining is the statistically meaningful element.

Roles of Data Mining

In data mining, it plays several important roles. These roles are:

  1. Understanding the concept
  2. Gathering the data
  3. Finding the patterns
  4. Reconstructing the data
  5. Understanding the meaning.

Data Mining Examples are used to explain the working process, in which the data has been collected. For example, a bank is interested in how to improve its accounting efficiency.

Data Mining Tools

With so many strategies to employ during data mining, it's critical to have the right tools to get the most out of your analytics. For successful implementation, these approaches usually need the use of multiple distinct tools or a tool with a broad set of skills.

Although businesses may utilize data science tools like R, Python, or Knime for machine learning analysis, it's critical to use a data governance solution to guarantee compliance and correct data lineage. Furthermore, to execute analytics, businesses will need to interact with repositories such as cloud data storage, as well as dashboards and data visualizations to give business information that users need to comprehend analysis.

Data Mining Concepts

The major concept in data mining is that it includes the concept of transforming one or more variables into another. Through data mining, an analyst can extract pertinent and useful data from data to be more effective in identifying and utilizing the content of data. The obtained information or data could be used to conclude, such as identifying the real market condition of a particular product or developing a policy for managing a financial institution. Important and interesting data elements may be identified through data mining such as transactions or other relevant information.

Data Mining Techniques

Cleaning and preparing data

Cleaning and preparing data is an important step in the data mining process. To be helpful in various analytic approaches, raw data must be cleaned and structured. Different components of data modeling, transformation, data migration, ETL, ELT, data integration, and aggregation are included in data cleaning and preparation. It's a vital step in determining the optimal use of data by knowing its basic characteristics and properties. The importance of data cleansing and preparation for the company is self-explanatory. Data is either worthless to an organization or untrustworthy owing to its quality if this initial stage is skipped.

Pattern recognition

Pattern recognition is a basic data mining technique. It entails detecting and tracking regularities in data to draw educated conclusions regarding business results. When a company notices a pattern in sales data, for example, there's a foundation for making decisions to monetize on the information. If a company discovers that a given product sells better than others for a particular group, it may utilize this information to develop comparable products or services, or just better stock the original product for this population.

Classification

The many properties linked with different types of data are analyzed using classification data mining techniques. Organizations can categorize or classify linked data after identifying the primary features of various data kinds. This is necessary for recognizing personally identifiable information that companies may want to safeguard or redact from documents, for example.

Association

Association is a statistical data mining approach. It denotes that some data (or data-driven events) are connected to other data or data-driven events. It's related to the concept of co-occurrence in machine learning, where the probability of one data drives happening more than once.

Detecting anomalies

Any abnormalities in databases are detected via outlier detection. When companies discover anomalies in their data, it becomes simpler to understand why they occur and plan for future occurrences to meet corporate goals. For example, if there is a rise in the use of transactional systems for credit card payments at a certain time of day, businesses may use this information to optimize their sales for the remainder of the day by working out why. Clustering is an analytics methodology that uses visual methods to comprehend data.Different colors are often used in clustering algorithms to depict data dispersion. Cluster analytics works well with graph methods. Users may visually examine how data is distributed and find trends that are important to their business objectives using graphs and clustering in particular.

Regression

Regression methods help determine the nature of a dataset's connection between variables. In some cases, the links might be causative, while in others, they could just be correlations. Regression is a simple white box approach for determining how variables are connected. Forecasting and data modeling both employ regression methods.

Prediction

Prediction is one of four areas of analytics and is a particularly strong element of data mining. Predictive analytics works by extending trends identified in current or historical data into the future. As a result, it provides companies with insight into what patterns may emerge in their data in the future. Using predictive analytics may be done in a variety of ways. Features of artificial intelligence and machine learning are used in some of the more advanced ones. Predictive analytics, on the other hand, does not have to rely on these approaches; it may also be aided by simpler algorithms.

Patterns that appear in a specific order

This data mining method focuses on finding a set of events that occur in a predetermined order. It's very helpful for mining transactional data. This method, for example, can indicate which articles of apparel clients are more likely to acquire after making a first purchase, such as a pair of shoes. Analyzing regularities can assist businesses in recommending additional products to clients to increase sales.

Trees of decision

Decision trees are a sort of prediction model that allows businesses to harvest data effectively. A decision tree is technically a type of machine learning, however, it is more commonly referred to as a white box machine learning approach. Users can easily see how the data inputs impact the outputs using a decision tree. A random forest is a predictive analytics model that is created by combining several decision tree models. Complicated random forest models are referred regarded as "black box" machine learning approaches since their outputs are not always straightforward to comprehend based on their inputs. However, in most situations, this fundamental type of ensembles simulation is more correct than relying only on decision trees.

Statistical methods

Statistical approaches are at the heart of the majority of data mining analyses. The various analytics models are based on statistical principles that provide numerical numbers that may be used to achieve certain business goals. In image recognition systems, neural networks, for example, utilize complicated statistics based on multiple weights and measurements to decide whether a picture is a dog or a cat. Statistical models are one of artificial intelligence's two primary disciplines. Some statistical approaches use static models, whereas others that use machine learning improve over time.

Neural networks are a type of computer network

A neural network is a sort of machine learning model that is frequently used in artificial intelligence and deep learning. Neural networks are one of the most effective machine learning techniques utilized today. They are named after the idea that they all have distinct layers that mirror the manner neurons operate in the human brain.Although a neural network may be a useful tool in data mining, organizations should exercise caution when utilizing it since some of these neural network models are quite complicated, making it difficult to comprehend how a neural network arrived at a result.

Visualization

Another essential aspect of data mining is data visualization. They provide users with access to data based on sensory impressions that may be seen. Modern data visualizations are versatile, suitable for broadcasting data in real-time, and distinguished by a variety of colors that indicate various data trends and patterns.Dashboards are a useful tool for uncovering data mining results via data visualizations. Instead of relying just on the numerical outputs of statistical models, organizations may create dashboards based on a variety of indicators and utilize visualizations to graphically emphasize trends in data.

Data warehousing

Data warehousing is a crucial process that refers to the storing of data. Data warehousing used to entail retaining structured data in relational database systems so that it could be examined for business intelligence, reporting, and basic dashboarding. Cloud data warehouses and database systems in semi-structured and unstructured data storage, such as Hadoop, are now available. While data warehouses were once used to store and analyze historical data, several current techniques can now provide in-depth, real-time data analysis.

Processing in the long-term memory

The capacity to evaluate material over long periods is referred to as long-term memory processing. This is when data warehouses' historical data comes in handy. When a company can do analytics over a long period, it can spot trends that might otherwise be difficult to notice. For example, a company may discover subtle indications to minimizing churn in finance by examining turnover over years.

Artificial intelligence and machine learning

Ai and machine learning are two of the most cutting-edge data mining technologies. When working with large amounts of data, advanced kinds of machine learning, such as deep learning, provide very accurate predictions. As a result, they're valuable in AI applications such as image recognition, voice recognition, and advanced text analytics utilizing Deep Neural Networks. These data mining approaches work well with semi-structured and unorganized data to extract value.

Conclusions

We hope that you have gained a better understanding of the various algorithms involved in data mining.

fields.title: The Data Mining Process: What It Is, How It Works, And Why You Need It
fields.body:
Data Mining, which is also known as Knowledge Discovery in Databases is a process of discovering useful information from large volumes of data stored in databases and data warehouses. This analysis is done for decision-making processes in the companies

What is Data Mining?

Data mining is the process of analyzing a vast array of structured and unstructured data to extract valuable insights. This is done for decision-making processes in the companies. The insights obtained through the data mining process provide the business users with the proper information that they need for better decision-making in their business. A data mine is an organized method for identifying, classifying, and aggregating the data found in a given system or application. Most of the time, business owners search for facts like sales figures, financial information, and even customer data in databases. Data mining, therefore, offers a quick and efficient way to discover these facts and do analysis on them to understand the future of the business.

How does Data Mining work?

The purpose of Data Mining is to provide advanced analysis to users. Data mining is conducted in terms of separating large amounts of data, for example using computer programs and algorithms to understand the meaning of the data. Through the analysis of the data, knowledge of current trends can be gained which can be then used to anticipate potential outcomes in the future. The data mining process itself is executed to gain insights and predict future outcomes of business strategies by using mathematical algorithms. An algorithm is a collection of steps that may be followed to solve a problem. It uses a set of rules and assumptions to find the answers to a problem.

The Data Mining Process

Data Mining is a complex analytical process that uses analytics to discover relationships and patterns that are hidden in large datasets. The major features of this process are Information gathering, In this process, the available data is used by data miners to get the information that is needed for a decision-making process. In this process, the available data is used by data miners to get the information that is needed for a decision-making process. Decomposition, This process is used to find specific values in large volumes of data. This process is used to find specific values in large volumes of data. Finding relationships is the most common process in Data Mining. It is the most preferred process for the customers.

The phases in the standard experimental approach applied to the data-mining task are as follows:

State the problem and construct a hypothesis

A modeler often provides a set of variables for an unknown dependence and, if feasible, a general kind of this relationship as the first hypothesis in this phase. At this point, there might be multiple theories for a single problem. The first stage necessitates knowledge of both an application area and a data-mining model. In reality, this entails a close collaboration between a data-mining specialist and an application expert. This collaboration does not end beyond the initial phase of ineffective data-mining applications.

Collect data

This stage is concerned with how data is created and collected In general, there are two unique options. The first is when the data-generation process is managed by a professional (modeler). This method is referred to as a planned experiment. The second scenario is when the expert has no control over the data production process. The observational approach is a term used to describe this method. In most data-mining applications, an observational context, essentially random data creation, is expected. Typically, sample distribution is completely unknown after data is gathered, or it is supplied only in part and implicitly throughout the data collecting operation.

Data Preparation

Data preparation should not be viewed apart from the rest of the data mining process. Every stage of the data-mining process might create new and better data sets for inflationary times if all activities worked together. In general, an accurate preparation approach combines prior knowledge inside application-specific scaling and encoding to give an optimum representation for a data-mining methodology.

Estimate model

The major goal during this phase is to choose and execute an adequate data-mining approach. This is not a simple procedure. In practice, implementation is usually based on several models.

Model interpretation and conclusions

In most situations, data-mining models should assist in making decisions. As a result, those simulations have to be decipherable to just be useful, as people are unlikely to make judgments based on complicated "black-box" simulations. It's worth noting that the aims of model accuracy and model interpretation accuracy are somewhat at odds. Simple models are usually easier to understand, and they're also rarely correct. Using high-dimensional models, modern data-mining technologies are intended to produce extremely accurate findings. The crucial issue of understanding these models is treated as a separate activity, with specialized approaches for validating outcomes.

Why is Data Mining Important?

To find the best matches for an existing or a potential customer to attract new clients, thereby increasing business revenue and expanding the customer base. Hence companies are moving towards data mining to increase their revenue and to cater to the changing demands of the customers. This type of analysis of data helps to build a business framework that allows companies to tailor the business plans and strategies to specific business needs and the needs of the target market. In addition, it is also used to build and use software that provides a better understanding of the users and helps in making a better profile.

Data mining has grown more common since the introduction of Big Data. Big data refers to extraordinarily massive collections of data that can be processed by computers to uncover human-understandable patterns, correlations, and trends. Big data contains a wealth of information on a wide range of topics. Simple statistics with manual intervention would not work with this quantity of data. The data mining procedure satisfies this need. As a result, basic data statistics are replaced by complicated data mining techniques.

The data mining method will automatically extract important information from raw data like transactions, photographs, pictures, and file systems, and analyze it to create reports that organizations may utilize to take action. As a result, the data mining process is critical for organizations to make better judgments by identifying patterns and trends in data, organizing the data, and removing relevant data.

The following are the most important issues in data mining:

  • Varied users have different needs when it comes to mining different types of knowledge from databases. Different types of knowledge may pique the expectations of various people. As a result, data mining must be able to handle a wide range of knowledge-finding activities.
  • Interactive knowledge mining at different levels of abstraction — This data mining process must be engaging as it enables applications to run on searching for patterns, submitting data mining requests, and modifying them depending mostly on supplied findings.
  • Background information may be utilized to drive the discovery process and represent found patterns not just in succinct words but also at many levels of abstraction.

Data mining query languages and ad-hoc data mining

A query language for data mining that lets users configure ad-hoc mining activities must be linked with a query language for database systems and optimized for effective and responsive data mining.

Data mining results presentation and visualization

Patterns must be articulated in high-level languages and visual representations after they have been found. Users should be able to grasp these representations readily.

Dealing with noisy or incomplete data

Data cleaning methods that can deal with noise and partial objects while mining data regularities are required. If data cleansing techniques aren't in place, the accuracy of patterns found will suffer.

Pattern evaluation

This relates to the problem's interest. The patterns found should be intriguing since they indicate either general knowledge or a lack of originality.

Data mining techniques' effectiveness and extensibility

Data mining algorithms should be flexible and effective to obtain information from large amounts of data in systems.

Mining methods that are simultaneous, dispersed, and progressive

The advancement of distributed and parallel data mining algorithms are inspired by variables such as large databases, a broad dispersion of data, and the intricacy of data mining techniques. Data is divided into divisions using these methods, which are then examined in parallel. The outcomes of the divisions are then combined. The incremental algorithms update databases without re-mining data from the beginning.

Conclusion

Several factors make it essential for all companies to have a data mining process in place. These factors include the increased availability of data, government policies, rapid technological changes, and the need for business strategy across multiple verticals. What is the difference between big data and machine learning? Big data is a broad concept. It’s the much-used term for big data, which has many different definitions. One of the important definitions of big data is how many data points are represented in a certain size and each time. A smaller amount of data is considered big. Hence the definition. If a company needs to make important business decisions, it needs to choose between Big Data or Machine Learning.
